The prepared GQDs@MIP represents a fluorescence emission peak at 420 nm upon excitation with wavelength of 365 nm (Fig. 4
                        ). As seen in Fig. 4, after template removal the fluorescence intensity of GQDs@MIP increased. Also, the fluorescence intensity of GQDs@MIP quenched greatly upon addition and interaction with METH molecules. The –COOH groups located at the surface of GQDs@MIP interact with METH molecules through the hydrogen bonding. It seems that upon incorporation of METH molecules into the cavities of GQDs@MIP, an energy transfer from excited GQDs@MIP to METH occurred which results in decreasing the GQD fluorescence intensity (Scheme 2
                        ). The results indicate that the prepared fluorescent GQDs@MIP can be utilized for efficient METH sensing.
